text: Also known as "into the deep".  The Shallows got good reviews, not sure why.  If you're looking for a good "shark" movie, this one is pretty good.  More of a thriller really, not just sharks.  It's pretty damn intense once it gets going.  Music is different and cool and really works well in the film.  The camera work is REALLY good.  Gives a good sense of the surroundings and puts you there.  Acting, while no oscars are coming from this, holds up.  Cool ending.  I was ready to be underwhelmed, but it surpassed my expectations.  I've watched it twice, and could watch it again.

text: I have been cage diving with great white sharks (Guadalupe island) and I can tell you this trailer has a slew of false info. First off, this guy's boat would've been spotted and pulled without permit. There are only several reliable spots to cage dive with great whites and they are heavily protected. Guadalupe island for example only hands out 11 licenses each season. The odds of seeing a great white randomly in an unreliable area, even with significant chum, are extremely small. Companies hang out in same areas too so a random boat would be spotted so fast it'd be silly. Second, when u cage dive real life each cage is double steel lined (each can hold a bus by itself), then u have a master diver with you (only time do not require one is if you are in a surface cage), then there are additional air tanks as well in case of emergency. They are setup in such a way that if both lines somehow did snap u just turn a valve and they fill up two containers which floats cage to surface. Finally, great whites are 100% not attracted to us, they could care less. These two girls (even with boat most likely long gone) could easily swim to surface and head inland. Great whites constantly move around. PS - One air tank would not have lasted that long till night time, not even close, and their ears would have been totally screwed up from a fall that quick bc of pressure change. Ok that's all for now. :)

text: this movie looks like such bullshit.  now I haven't seen the movie, and I'm no expert so take my thoughts with a grain of salt but...  -These sharks are pretty unrealistically large, even for great white standards and the special effects on them could definitely use some improvement  -also...FORTY-SEVEN METERS!?! now I'm no scuba diving expert but that's 154 feet! that's the distance of a 15 story building! and I'm pretty sure that descending that deep THAT fast, the pressure alone at 36 lb psi is probably enough to kill em if not cause serious damage!   -also, if they want to reach the top without dying from the benz,¬†they have to ascend at no faster than 30 ft a minute. now, if they were experienced divers and weren't being harassed by sharks this would take about 5 minutes to ascend. But there's also the factor of their air tanks!!  -It is unknown how much air they used before the accident. but with the pressure compressing the air and their heavy breathing and screaming, it's safe to say they depleted it pretty quickly, so their chances of surviving are slim at best.   so overall, judging by its trailer, this movie looks very poorly written. these characters seem so uninteresting, the story just isn't there, and I only imagine the ungodly amounts of filler to make this movie stretch to an hour and a half.  and that's my two cents.

text: I'm really upset about how sharks are represented nowadays. Sharks don't prey on humans on purpose, they eat seals, they think humans taste bad. If they attack, it's most likely they mistaked you as a seal, you moved around too much, or you wore bright/shiny stuff underwater.   Sharks are going extinct because people eat them for food, and because they're afraid of them. Sharks are actually very curious, intelligent creatures. *They're water puppies.* The more sharks are killed, the higher the seal population. These means that fish, the food source for seals, will go down as well, ruining business for many people, and many people in foreign countries will starve, as seafood is their main source of nutrition.   It is Jaws, and movies like this one that shouldn't be encouraged. I really don't want to watch some movie about stupid ass teenage white girls with sharks, and then turning them turning the sharks into the bad guy. *Please don't watch this movie, save the sharks.*

text: Completely unrealistic. For anyone who doesn't know about scuba, the deeper you go the less time your air will last. It's basic scuba knowledge. At the depth of 47 meters, they would run out of air and be dead in 10 minutes tops. That varies of course depending on the tank size and kind of air in the tank (varies a small bit) but the basic scuba gear, which I'm assuming they would be using in this scenario, they would run out of air in 5 minutes at that depth. I hate movies like this that don't even do basic research on key concepts of the story they are trying to tell.

text: I watched this movie. Slight spoiler alert. So, I need to know what gear they used! A full face mask with no nose clamp, that allows them to equalize and not blow out their eardrums at a rate of decent exceeding 300 feet per minute? I must have it! And, they're diving with what looks like Aluminum 50s, and have enough air to stay at about 150 ft. for over an hour! Even using two tanks, that's incredible! And, changing your first stage underwater, that's a capability I would like to have! But why didn't they send them tanks with regulators already attached? And how to they not get narc'd beyond belief until the second tank magically had an effect similar acid and shrooms, washed down with absinthe? I won't even bother talking about what happens in the hallucination, and the ruptured lungs that would have killed them all instantly... And those "Deep Sea Divers" from the coastguard diving singles? WOW!!! As a diver with 5 different certifications, including NASE Advanced OWD and a PADI Rescue Diver, I find this movie to be so cringe-worthy it becomes more of a comedy than a horror movie.... but, hey, at least they tried, right? lol

text: This is how the movie would go down (pardon the pun) real life. Cable breaks and divers rocket down to 47m in less than a minute, they eardrums rupture form the sudden uncontrolled descent and inability to valsalva that fast. The inexperienced divers are struck with the vertigo induced from the water rushing into their perforated ears, with the panic of suddenly being dropped so deep and the buzz of narcosis, its not unlikely they'd puke in their mask. If they can't figure out how to clear the puke from their mask in their disoriented state they drown in their vomit, if they do, or don't puke in the first place their single 80 tank of air at 47m (unless your calm as zen and a cardio hero) will last roughly 20 minutes of breathing (not a very long movie), they also have depending on your tables roughly 5-10 minutes window where they can ascend without decompression. The ascent can't be too fast without risking arterial gas embolism (AGE) though and without fins you'd need some air in the BC to get up, especially from so deep, if they lose control of their ascent rate they'll be rocketing up risking AGE. Also theres a hungry shark and their ears are bleeding so yeah.

You can hear sound(good to do) making you prone to ear drums popping so you dont hear sound. Water adds 1 atmosphere of presser per 10 metres.  And sharks dont attack scuba divers unless they are really really hungry. They are scared of the bubbles.  I just needed to get my thoughts out.
